00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:50.250 align:middle line:84%
stimulus package that passed the
United States Congress, deep,

00:21:50.250 --> 00:21:54.220 align:middle line:84%
deep, deep tax breaks for
cars that weighed 6,000 pounds

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:55.020 align:middle line:90%
or more?

00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:56.410 align:middle line:90%
It was just a list of cars.

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:57.210 align:middle line:90%
Those cars?

00:21:57.210 --> 00:21:58.110 align:middle line:90%
Those are just cars.

00:21:58.110 --> 00:21:59.100 align:middle line:90%
These cars?

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:00.720 align:middle line:90%
Economic stimulus.

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:02.640 align:middle line:84%
In World War II, we
went from producing

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:04.830 align:middle line:84%
Studebakers and
Buicks to producing

00:22:04.830 --> 00:22:08.820 align:middle line:84%
Sherman tanks and long-range
bombers in a matter of a month.

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:10.950 align:middle line:84%
And you're telling
me you can't produce

00:22:10.950 --> 00:22:15.010 align:middle line:84%
a car that gets better
than 26 miles per gallon?

00:22:15.010 --> 00:22:15.910 align:middle line:90%
Look at Toyota.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:18.820 align:middle line:84%
They've become the number-one
car company in the world,

00:22:18.820 --> 00:22:21.460 align:middle line:84%
largely due to the
popularity of the Prius.

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:26.200 align:middle line:10%
>> Toyota made the choice to
build hybrids when the American

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:28.750 align:middle line:10%
companies made the
choice at the same time.

00:22:28.750 --> 00:22:29.680 align:middle line:10%
They had the options.

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:31.210 align:middle line:90%
They had hybrids on the books.

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:32.350 align:middle line:90%
They could have done it.

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:35.020 align:middle line:84%
But they took a
short-term view and Toyota

00:22:35.020 --> 00:22:37.030 align:middle line:90%
took a long-term view.

00:22:37.030 --> 00:22:39.400 align:middle line:10%
>> I wanted a more
fuel-efficient car,

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:41.952 align:middle line:10%
not so much because I'm
some kind of do gooder,

00:22:41.952 --> 00:22:44.410 align:middle line:10%
only because I don't like going
to the gas station all that

00:22:44.410 --> 00:22:45.210 align:middle line:10%
much.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:46.780 align:middle line:90%
>> People are buying Priuses.

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:49.910 align:middle line:84%
And they're buying them because
they're making a statement.

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:52.780 align:middle line:84%
The same thing with diesel cars,
people are buying diesel cars

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:55.090 align:middle line:84%
and they're importing them
into the United States.

00:22:55.090 --> 00:22:57.130 align:middle line:84%
After all, you
can pour biodiesel

00:22:57.130 --> 00:23:00.340 align:middle line:84%
straight into a diesel
car with no modifications.

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:03.040 align:middle line:10%
I searched the whole auto
show for diesel vehicles.

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:07.090 align:middle line:84%
I only found one, the V10
Touareg that Volkswagen

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:09.340 align:middle line:90%
raced across Africa.

00:23:09.340 --> 00:23:11.860 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't for sale.

00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:15.400 align:middle line:10%
>> Based on their experience,
Americans know that diesels are

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:17.620 align:middle line:10%
noisy, and smoky, and slow.

00:23:17.620 --> 00:23:19.840 align:middle line:84%
That's not what diesel
technology is today.

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:21.670 align:middle line:84%
That's not what's
coming out of Europe.

00:23:21.670 --> 00:23:25.030 align:middle line:84%
What they call common-rail,
turbocharged diesels

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:26.080 align:middle line:90%
are phenomenal.

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:29.310 align:middle line:10%
>> Diesel engines have changed
dramatically in the last 15

00:23:29.310 --> 00:23:30.490 align:middle line:10%
to 20 years.

00:23:30.490 --> 00:23:33.880 align:middle line:84%
Beginning in 2007, the
emissions standards

00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:38.070 align:middle line:84%
for diesel vehicles and gasoline
vehicles will become the same.

00:23:38.070 --> 00:23:40.570 align:middle line:10%
>> And of course, you're going
to get something on the order

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:43.030 align:middle line:10%
of 30% improvement
in fuel economy.

00:23:43.030 --> 00:23:45.190 align:middle line:10%
In some models, it's
even more than that.

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:47.680 align:middle line:10%
If you're worried about
CO2 and global warming--

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:51.730 align:middle line:10%
>> Biodiesel causes reduction
in emissions of certain toxic

00:23:51.730 --> 00:23:52.870 align:middle line:10%
compounds.

00:23:52.870 --> 00:23:56.290 align:middle line:84%
>> In Germany, an independent
car company called Loremo just

00:23:56.290 --> 00:24:00.410 align:middle line:84%
produced a diesel car that
gets over 150 miles per gallon.

00:24:00.410 --> 00:24:02.140 align:middle line:84%
>> That's why,
especially in Europe,

00:24:02.140 --> 00:24:04.100 align:middle line:84%
they've just gone hog
wild over buying diesels.

00:24:04.100 --> 00:24:04.900 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:08.850 align:middle line:84%
>> Bill Ford, CEO, Chairman,
Ford Motor Company.

00:24:08.850 --> 00:24:09.650 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:14.780 align:middle line:84%
>> In 2006, Ford
lost $12.7 billion.

00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:17.390 align:middle line:84%
>> Thomas LaSorda,
CEO and President,

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:19.550 align:middle line:90%
Daimler Chrysler Corporation.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:24.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Chrysler cut 13,000
jobs and lost $1.5 billion.

00:24:24.890 --> 00:24:27.170 align:middle line:84%
>> Rick Wagner
Jr., Chairman, CEO,

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:28.445 align:middle line:90%
General Motors corporation.

00:24:28.445 --> 00:24:30.020 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:30.020 --> 00:24:32.810 align:middle line:90%
>> GM cut 35,000 jobs.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:45.140 align:middle line:90%
They lost $10.6 billion.

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:51.500 align:middle line:10%
>> Why the heck can't
all of America's cars run

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:54.380 align:middle line:10%
on electricity and
advanced biofuels?

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:55.430 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:57.908 align:middle line:10%
>> When Detroit-- they were
shown that they would save

00:24:57.908 --> 00:25:00.200 align:middle line:10%
millions of lives if they
put seat belts in their cars,

00:25:00.200 --> 00:25:01.423 align:middle line:10%
they resisted it.

00:25:01.423 --> 00:25:02.840 align:middle line:10%
And they didn't
do it because they

00:25:02.840 --> 00:25:05.210 align:middle line:10%
thought it was the morally
right thing to do, which it was.

00:25:05.210 --> 00:25:06.585 align:middle line:10%
They didn't do it
until they were

00:25:06.585 --> 00:25:08.270 align:middle line:10%
forced to do it by legislation.

00:25:08.270 --> 00:25:10.340 align:middle line:84%
And we're in the
same place right now.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:13.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Consumers can choose
to buy the Prius instead

00:25:13.460 --> 00:25:14.330 align:middle line:90%
of the Hummer.

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:18.170 align:middle line:84%
And governments can choose to
subsidize the Prius instead

00:25:18.170 --> 00:25:19.490 align:middle line:90%
of the Hummer.

00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:22.220 align:middle line:84%
>> Because our government
subsidizes wasteful cars,

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:26.360 align:middle line:84%
the average American car is
30% bigger than those overseas,

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:31.700 align:middle line:84%
which means our cars also
consume about 30% more fuel.

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:33.890 align:middle line:10%
With the largest car
fleet in the world,

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:38.180 align:middle line:10%
our population, only 4.5%
of the Earth's inhabitants,

00:25:38.180 --> 00:25:41.150 align:middle line:10%
makes almost half of the
world's automotive CO2.

00:25:41.150 --> 00:25:44.920 align:middle line:90%


00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:48.730 align:middle line:10%
I went to see Colin Campbell,
renowned oil geologist,

00:25:48.730 --> 00:25:52.180 align:middle line:10%
and author of the book,
"The Coming Oil Crisis."

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:54.460 align:middle line:10%
Colin showed me "The
Oil and Gas Journal,"

00:25:54.460 --> 00:25:56.650 align:middle line:10%
in which ExxonMobil
first printed

00:25:56.650 --> 00:26:00.650 align:middle line:10%
the graph that shows that our
planet's oil supply is running

00:26:00.650 --> 00:26:01.450 align:middle line:10%
out.

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:06.700 align:middle line:10%
>> 1981, the world started
using more than it found.

00:26:06.700 --> 00:26:08.800 align:middle line:10%
And the gap is widening.

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:11.470 align:middle line:10%
>> Colin and ExxonMobil
are not alone.

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:15.160 align:middle line:10%
Hundreds of books, thousands of
websites, and countless charts

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:17.800 align:middle line:10%
show that our oil
is running out.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:21.160 align:middle line:84%
Even Matthew Simmons, who heads
the world's largest oil bank

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:24.220 align:middle line:84%
and has testified in
front of Congress, agrees.

00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:27.940 align:middle line:10%
>> Oil is actually
non-renewable,

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:30.490 align:middle line:10%
even though there are some
economists that now believe

00:26:30.490 --> 00:26:32.020 align:middle line:10%
that maybe it
really is renewable.

00:26:32.020 --> 00:26:33.640 align:middle line:10%
And that is preposterous.

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:35.770 align:middle line:84%
We have a society,
in the United States,

00:26:35.770 --> 00:26:37.630 align:middle line:84%
more than any other
country on Earth,

00:26:37.630 --> 00:26:42.070 align:middle line:84%
has an enormous appetite for
oil for our daily well-being.

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:46.180 align:middle line:84%
And we are blindly assuming
that the more we need,

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:48.730 align:middle line:84%
the more we will have,
because we need it so much,

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:52.780 align:middle line:84%
and that since we have never
run out, we will never run out.

00:26:52.780 --> 00:26:55.420 align:middle line:84%
>> We consume 25%
of the world's oil.

00:26:55.420 --> 00:26:58.720 align:middle line:84%
We have 2% of the world's
oil, all of our reserves.

00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:03.110 align:middle line:84%
We cannot drill our
way out of this.

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:04.340 align:middle line:90%
>> This is Ken Hern.

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:07.040 align:middle line:90%
He's a former CEO at Texaco.

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:10.160 align:middle line:84%
If anyone knows about
oil, it's this guy.

00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:12.920 align:middle line:84%
>> As we stand today, it's
getting harder to find it.

00:27:12.920 --> 00:27:15.560 align:middle line:10%
It's getting very hard to find
it in a Western hemisphere,

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:16.670 align:middle line:10%
if you will.

00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:18.740 align:middle line:10%
I'll give you my best
example I can give you.

00:27:18.740 --> 00:27:21.260 align:middle line:84%
Chevron has announced
the possibility of oil

00:27:21.260 --> 00:27:23.330 align:middle line:90%
being in the Gulf of Mexico.

00:27:23.330 --> 00:27:25.340 align:middle line:84%
But the area they're
going to go drill

00:27:25.340 --> 00:27:29.870 align:middle line:84%
in, they're going to drill
in 10,000 feet of water,

00:27:29.870 --> 00:27:34.862 align:middle line:84%
5,000 feet of silt. They'll be
15,000 feet below the surface

00:27:34.862 --> 00:27:36.320 align:middle line:84%
before they hit
the structure where

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:38.032 align:middle line:90%
they're going to try to drill.

00:27:38.032 --> 00:27:39.740 align:middle line:84%
If you think about
it, it would be easier

00:27:39.740 --> 00:27:41.750 align:middle line:84%
to walk on the face
of the moon than it

00:27:41.750 --> 00:27:44.270 align:middle line:84%
would be to go to that
sector of this blue planet

00:27:44.270 --> 00:27:45.380 align:middle line:90%
and look for oil.

00:27:45.380 --> 00:27:47.713 align:middle line:10%
>> The big question, Josh,
is what are we're going to do

00:27:47.713 --> 00:27:51.920 align:middle line:10%
in 25 years time, when the
oil is seriously depleted?

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:56.547 align:middle line:90%


00:27:56.547 --> 00:27:58.880 align:middle line:10%
>> Of course, this isn't the
first time we've had an oil

00:27:58.880 --> 00:27:59.680 align:middle line:10%
shortage.

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:11.350 align:middle line:90%


00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:15.100 align:middle line:84%
Back in 1973, OPEC
cut the flow of oil

00:28:15.100 --> 00:28:17.050 align:middle line:84%
off to punish the
US for supporting

00:28:17.050 --> 00:28:20.370 align:middle line:90%
Israel in the Yom Kippur War.

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:22.230 align:middle line:84%
When Jimmy Carter
became president,

00:28:22.230 --> 00:28:25.380 align:middle line:84%
he responded by launching an
ambitious program to reduce

00:28:25.380 --> 00:28:27.210 align:middle line:90%
our dependence on foreign oil.

00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:29.130 align:middle line:84%
He even had solar
panels installed

00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:30.810 align:middle line:90%
on the roof of the White House.

00:28:30.810 --> 00:28:34.380 align:middle line:84%
>> We must start now to develop
the new unconventional sources

00:28:34.380 --> 00:28:37.620 align:middle line:84%
of energy that we will rely
on in the next century.

00:28:37.620 --> 00:28:39.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Carter's plan was working.

00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:41.250 align:middle line:84%
And by the time
he left office, he

00:28:41.250 --> 00:28:44.585 align:middle line:84%
had reduced America's
energy use by 25%.

00:28:44.585 --> 00:28:46.710 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a problem that we
will not be able to solve

00:28:46.710 --> 00:28:48.660 align:middle line:90%
in the next few years.

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:50.430 align:middle line:84%
And it's likely to get
progressively worse

00:28:50.430 --> 00:28:53.250 align:middle line:84%
through the rest
of this century.

00:28:53.250 --> 00:28:56.730 align:middle line:84%
>> After Carter left office,
the Reagan administration took

00:28:56.730 --> 00:28:58.590 align:middle line:90%
the solar panels down.

00:28:58.590 --> 00:29:00.870 align:middle line:84%
>> They even cut the
fuel-economy standards.

00:29:00.870 --> 00:29:04.120 align:middle line:10%
We had a nice, rising trend
of fuel economy standards.

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:05.760 align:middle line:10%
And they were notched
back under Reagan

00:29:05.760 --> 00:29:07.800 align:middle line:10%
just to encourage bigger cars.

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:11.370 align:middle line:10%
>> The perception of that
administration was there are no

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:13.860 align:middle line:10%
real energy problems that
the market cannot solve.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:15.690 align:middle line:10%
We don't need any more policies.

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:18.300 align:middle line:10%
And in fact, we haven't
had any real energy

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:20.670 align:middle line:10%
policies since the
Carter administration.

00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:23.010 align:middle line:84%
>> Since the Reagan
administration,

00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:27.270 align:middle line:84%
we've had this attitude of, it's
good to consume as much as you

00:29:27.270 --> 00:29:29.670 align:middle line:84%
can because that makes
everybody richer.

00:29:29.670 --> 00:29:31.750 align:middle line:90%
And of course, it's a huge lie.

00:29:31.750 --> 00:29:33.690 align:middle line:84%
Every president, going
back to Richard Nixon,

00:29:33.690 --> 00:29:36.370 align:middle line:84%
has watched the increasing
reliance on foreign oil,

00:29:36.370 --> 00:29:37.170 align:middle line:90%
steadily.

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:41.840 align:middle line:90%


00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:43.640 align:middle line:84%
>> Before Jimmy Carter
became president,

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:45.740 align:middle line:90%
he was a peanut farmer.

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:48.590 align:middle line:84%
What business was our recent
president and vice president

00:29:48.590 --> 00:29:50.970 align:middle line:84%
engaged in before
they took office?

00:29:50.970 --> 00:29:52.670 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't peanut farming.

00:29:52.670 --> 00:29:55.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Of course, President
Bush is a Texas oilman.

00:29:55.700 --> 00:29:58.520 align:middle line:84%
It was Texas oil that
put him into office.

00:29:58.520 --> 00:30:01.970 align:middle line:84%
And there's no way he
can ever pass legislation

00:30:01.970 --> 00:30:06.920 align:middle line:84%
that will seriously harm the
oil and petroleum industry.

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:09.200 align:middle line:84%
>> According to the Center
for Public Integrity,

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:12.680 align:middle line:84%
the oil industry spent
more than $420 million,

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:17.300 align:middle line:84%
between 1998 and 2004, funding
politicians and political

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:18.770 align:middle line:90%
parties.

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:22.530 align:middle line:84%
ExxonMobil came in first,
giving $60 million.

00:30:22.530 --> 00:30:24.920 align:middle line:90%
Chevron-Texaco gave $40 million.

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:28.040 align:middle line:90%
And BP gave $30 million.

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:31.475 align:middle line:10%
This really begs the question,
is our government for sale?

00:30:31.475 --> 00:30:35.280 align:middle line:90%


00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:38.940 align:middle line:10%
Several months before 9/11,
Vice President Dick Cheney

00:30:38.940 --> 00:30:43.530 align:middle line:10%
held 40 secret meetings with the
heads of major oil companies.

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:47.280 align:middle line:10%
>> In those meetings, it was
obvious that the oil companies

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:50.160 align:middle line:10%
were writing energy
policy for our country.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:52.800 align:middle line:10%
>> Documents pertaining
to Cheney's meetings,

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:55.110 align:middle line:10%
released through the
Freedom of Information Act,

00:30:55.110 --> 00:30:57.540 align:middle line:10%
were purposefully blanked out.

00:30:57.540 --> 00:31:00.480 align:middle line:10%
However, the Justice
Department released maps

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:04.380 align:middle line:10%
from the meetings that showed
the oil companies discussed

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:09.090 align:middle line:10%
Iraqi oil pipelines, oil
refineries, and oil fields.

00:31:09.090 --> 00:31:14.040 align:middle line:84%
Iraq had the second-largest
oil reserves in the world.

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:22.190 align:middle line:84%
The maps were dated March,
2001, six months before 9/11.

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:24.890 align:middle line:10%
>> When we tried to
swear them to an oath,

00:31:24.890 --> 00:31:29.930 align:middle line:10%
the Republican majority refused
to have them take the oath.

00:31:29.930 --> 00:31:31.010 align:middle line:10%
It was outrageous.

00:31:31.010 --> 00:31:32.510 align:middle line:10%
>> We look forward to questions.

00:31:32.510 --> 00:31:33.325 align:middle line:10%
Senator Cantwell?

00:31:33.325 --> 00:31:35.450 align:middle line:10%
>> Mr. Chairman, I would
like the committee to vote

00:31:35.450 --> 00:31:36.808 align:middle line:10%
on whether we swear--

00:31:36.808 --> 00:31:37.850 align:middle line:10%
>> There will be no vote.

00:31:37.850 --> 00:31:39.200 align:middle line:10%
That's not in order at all.

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:41.060 align:middle line:10%
It's the decision
of the chairman.

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:42.620 align:middle line:10%
And I have made that decision.

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:46.010 align:middle line:10%
>> Mr. Chairman, I move that
we swear in the witnesses.

00:31:46.010 --> 00:31:47.630 align:middle line:10%
>> And I rule that out of order.

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:48.622 align:middle line:10%
>> I second the motion.

00:31:48.622 --> 00:31:49.580 align:middle line:10%
>> Thank you very much.

00:31:49.580 --> 00:31:51.800 align:middle line:10%
