biggest newspaper in France,

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:18.980 align:middle line:10%
"Le Monde," was, we're
all Americans now.

00:42:18.980 --> 00:42:22.430 align:middle line:10%
And for three weeks after
9/11, tens of thousands

00:42:22.430 --> 00:42:25.880 align:middle line:10%
of Muslim people in Tehran
came out onto the streets

00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:28.610 align:middle line:10%
to have spontaneous
candlelight vigils,

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:31.340 align:middle line:10%
to express their
solidarity, their sympathy,

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:33.840 align:middle line:10%
their love for the
United States of America.

00:42:33.840 --> 00:42:38.010 align:middle line:10%
We were the most-beloved nation
on the face of the planet.

00:42:38.010 --> 00:42:41.990 align:middle line:84%
And it took 230 years of
disciplined, restrained,

00:42:41.990 --> 00:42:44.450 align:middle line:84%
visionary leadership by
Republican and Democratic

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:47.420 align:middle line:84%
presidents to build up
those vast reservoirs

00:42:47.420 --> 00:42:49.640 align:middle line:84%
of public adoration
for the United States

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:52.200 align:middle line:90%
and for our values.

00:42:52.200 --> 00:42:55.020 align:middle line:84%
Through monumental
arrogance and incompetence,

00:42:55.020 --> 00:42:58.770 align:middle line:84%
these oil slaves
in the White House

00:42:58.770 --> 00:43:01.770 align:middle line:84%
have drained those
reservoirs dry.

00:43:01.770 --> 00:43:04.020 align:middle line:84%
And to me, that is
the bitterest pill

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:07.200 align:middle line:84%
to swallow because I saw in
the faces of those crowds when

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:10.050 align:middle line:84%
I was a little boy,
the hope for leadership

00:43:10.050 --> 00:43:11.640 align:middle line:84%
from the United
States, not just to do

00:43:11.640 --> 00:43:14.730 align:middle line:84%
good things for our country,
but to do great things for all

00:43:14.730 --> 00:43:15.570 align:middle line:90%
of humanity.

00:43:15.570 --> 00:43:22.240 align:middle line:90%


00:43:22.240 --> 00:43:25.630 align:middle line:84%
Abraham Lincoln said that
America is a great nation

00:43:25.630 --> 00:43:27.580 align:middle line:90%
because we are a good nation.

00:43:27.580 --> 00:43:30.310 align:middle line:84%
And he said, if we ever
stop being a good nation,

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:32.470 align:middle line:84%
we'll quickly lose
our greatness as well.

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:35.410 align:middle line:90%


00:43:35.410 --> 00:43:39.190 align:middle line:84%
Because of our addiction to
oil, we have lost that greatness

00:43:39.190 --> 00:43:40.870 align:middle line:90%
because we lost our goodness.

00:43:40.870 --> 00:43:43.810 align:middle line:10%
We put the oil in front
of the Bill of Rights.

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:46.570 align:middle line:90%


00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:48.370 align:middle line:84%
This isn't a great
nation just because it's

00:43:48.370 --> 00:43:51.160 align:middle line:84%
a place where you can come and
make a big pile for yourself,

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:53.410 align:middle line:84%
and whoever dies with
the most stuff wins.

00:43:53.410 --> 00:43:56.722 align:middle line:84%
It's good because of the values
that we're proud of, that we

00:43:56.722 --> 00:43:57.805 align:middle line:90%
pass down to our children.

00:43:57.805 --> 00:44:07.090 align:middle line:90%


00:44:07.090 --> 00:44:10.920 align:middle line:84%
>> This is a crucial time for
our country and our world.

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:13.680 align:middle line:84%
The changes we need to
make are monumental.

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:18.530 align:middle line:84%
The challenges we face
are almost insurmountable.

00:44:18.530 --> 00:44:23.030 align:middle line:84%
Robert Kennedy's father often
said, "Some men see things

00:44:23.030 --> 00:44:27.300 align:middle line:90%
as they are and say, why?

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:32.150 align:middle line:84%
I dream of things that never
were, and say, why not?

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:37.120 align:middle line:90%


00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:40.990 align:middle line:10%
America isn't the only country
that suffers from its addiction

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:42.250 align:middle line:10%
to oil.

00:44:42.250 --> 00:44:44.437 align:middle line:10%
I wanted to see how
other nations are

00:44:44.437 --> 00:44:45.520 align:middle line:10%
dealing with this problem.

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:53.640 align:middle line:90%


00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:56.850 align:middle line:10%
The citizens of Germany
demanded renewable energy.

00:44:56.850 --> 00:45:00.240 align:middle line:84%
And their government responded
by investing billions

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:05.220 align:middle line:84%
of dollars into solar, wind,
and biodiesel technologies.

00:45:05.220 --> 00:45:08.370 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't surprised to learn that
one of their greatest thinkers

00:45:08.370 --> 00:45:11.310 align:middle line:84%
had also been a big
proponent of green energy.

00:45:11.310 --> 00:45:22.250 align:middle line:90%


00:45:22.250 --> 00:45:24.690 align:middle line:10%
>> In the MAN-Museum, we
present the world's first diesel

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:25.490 align:middle line:10%
engine.

00:45:25.490 --> 00:45:30.110 align:middle line:10%
And also a very important part
is the diary of Rudolf Diesel.

00:45:30.110 --> 00:45:32.270 align:middle line:84%
>> So this is his
actual original diary?

00:45:32.270 --> 00:45:33.750 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:34.550 align:middle line:90%
Some notes.

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:40.360 align:middle line:90%


00:45:40.360 --> 00:45:44.830 align:middle line:84%
>> Rudolf Christian Karl Diesel
is born in Paris, in 1858,

00:45:44.830 --> 00:45:47.020 align:middle line:90%
to German parents.

00:45:47.020 --> 00:45:50.830 align:middle line:84%
He's a shy boy who spends
much of his time drawing.

00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:53.710 align:middle line:84%
He shows an interest in
all things mechanical,

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:57.100 align:middle line:84%
and often takes apart
the family cuckoo clock.

00:45:57.100 --> 00:46:01.780 align:middle line:84%
On his 14th birthday, Rudolf
announces his purpose in life.

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:06.820 align:middle line:84%
He is to become an engineer,
the best engineer in the world.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:10.450 align:middle line:84%
He excels in school, winning
scholarship after scholarship,

00:46:10.450 --> 00:46:13.900 align:middle line:84%
in some schools, earning the
highest scores ever recorded.

00:46:13.900 --> 00:46:17.090 align:middle line:84%
He learns to speak three
languages, German, French,

00:46:17.090 --> 00:46:19.270 align:middle line:90%
and English.

00:46:19.270 --> 00:46:21.820 align:middle line:84%
In 1880, Rudolf starts
an apprenticeship

00:46:21.820 --> 00:46:24.560 align:middle line:84%
building refrigeration
and steam engines.

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:27.130 align:middle line:84%
He's appalled at the
inefficiency of the steam

00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:28.750 align:middle line:90%
engine.

00:46:28.750 --> 00:46:32.770 align:middle line:84%
In 1892, he patents a
design for revolutionary,

00:46:32.770 --> 00:46:36.850 align:middle line:84%
highly-efficient new
engine, German patent number

00:46:36.850 --> 00:46:44.010 align:middle line:84%
6721, the machine we know
as the diesel engine.

00:46:44.010 --> 00:46:48.600 align:middle line:10%
He becomes a millionaire many
times over by the age of 40.

00:46:48.600 --> 00:46:53.610 align:middle line:84%
He debuts his engine at the
Paris Exhibition of 1900.

00:46:53.610 --> 00:46:57.320 align:middle line:90%
The engine runs on peanut oil.

00:46:57.320 --> 00:47:00.110 align:middle line:84%
More than 50 million
people attend.

00:47:00.110 --> 00:47:01.760 align:middle line:90%
The escalator is introduced.

00:47:01.760 --> 00:47:05.740 align:middle line:84%
And the first publicly-exhibited
films with sound are shown.

00:47:05.740 --> 00:47:10.660 align:middle line:10%
But Rudolf's engine wins the
Grand Prix, the highest prize.

00:47:10.660 --> 00:47:13.120 align:middle line:10%
It was his hope that
by fueling an engine

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:16.630 align:middle line:10%
with an agricultural product,
he could take the power away

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:18.910 align:middle line:10%
from big industry,
and put it back

00:47:18.910 --> 00:47:24.490 align:middle line:10%
into the hands of the everyday
farmer and the common man.

00:47:24.490 --> 00:47:28.030 align:middle line:84%
In 1913, Rudolf says goodbye
to his wife and children

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:31.980 align:middle line:84%
to go to the opening of a diesel
engine factory in England.

00:47:31.980 --> 00:47:34.830 align:middle line:10%
He boards the SS
Dresden at Antwerp

00:47:34.830 --> 00:47:37.050 align:middle line:10%
to cross the English Channel.

00:47:37.050 --> 00:47:39.060 align:middle line:10%
After dining with
the ship's captain,

00:47:39.060 --> 00:47:43.090 align:middle line:10%
he retires to his cabin,
about 10 o'clock that night.

00:47:43.090 --> 00:47:47.140 align:middle line:84%
The captain later says he
appeared to be in good spirits.

00:47:47.140 --> 00:47:50.760 align:middle line:84%
The next morning, Rudolf
Diesel is missing.

00:47:50.760 --> 00:47:56.200 align:middle line:90%


00:47:56.200 --> 00:47:58.970 align:middle line:84%
The ship is searched
to no avail.

00:47:58.970 --> 00:48:03.550 align:middle line:84%
The final entry of his journal
is a simple drawing of a cross.

00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:06.160 align:middle line:84%
A few days later,
his lifeless body

00:48:06.160 --> 00:48:10.650 align:middle line:84%
was found floating,
by fishermen.

00:48:10.650 --> 00:48:14.985 align:middle line:84%
The engine that he created over
100 years ago still runs today.

00:48:14.985 --> 00:48:18.800 align:middle line:90%


00:48:18.800 --> 00:48:21.020 align:middle line:10%
After Diesel's
death, Standard Oil

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:23.960 align:middle line:10%
introduced a dirty byproduct
of the gasoline distillation

00:48:23.960 --> 00:48:27.170 align:middle line:10%
process that could
run a diesel engine.

00:48:27.170 --> 00:48:29.165 align:middle line:90%
They call it diesel fuel.

00:48:29.165 --> 00:48:39.062 align:middle line:90%


00:48:39.062 --> 00:48:43.720 align:middle line:84%
Germany has over 1,900 public
filling stations for biodiesel.

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:44.800 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:48.080 align:middle line:84%
>> It's good for
our Mother Earth.

00:48:48.080 --> 00:48:51.460 align:middle line:84%
>> A lot of people want to
save the planet, but even more,

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:53.120 align:middle line:90%
want to save something else.

00:48:53.120 --> 00:48:53.920 align:middle line:90%
>> It's cheaper.

00:48:53.920 --> 00:48:55.570 align:middle line:90%
>> The price is cheaper.

00:48:55.570 --> 00:48:57.850 align:middle line:10%
>> Without any help
from the government,

00:48:57.850 --> 00:49:00.230 align:middle line:10%
biodiesel production
would not be competitive.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:03.310 align:middle line:84%
So government offers a
tax break for biodiesel.

00:49:03.310 --> 00:49:07.570 align:middle line:84%
The effect is that it's sold at
gas stations up to 15% cheaper

00:49:07.570 --> 00:49:08.620 align:middle line:90%
than ordinary diesel.

00:49:08.620 --> 00:49:11.930 align:middle line:90%


00:49:11.930 --> 00:49:15.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Biodiesel has become such a
hot topic in Germany that even

00:49:15.140 --> 00:49:17.140 align:middle line:84%
their pop culture heroes
